'''Max Pemberton''' is the [[pen name]] of a British medical doctor, journalist and author.<ref name="bmjcareers">{{Cite web | last = Asprey | first = Donald | title = 15 minutes with... The man behind Trust Me, I’m A (Junior) Doctor | work = BMJ Careers | date = 2010-06-02 | url = http://careers.bmj.com/careers/advice/view-article.html?id=20001065 |accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref> He works full-time as a psychiatrist in the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS).<ref name="bmjcareers"></ref> He is a columnist for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', writing comment on news events concerning culture, social and ethical issues, the politics of health care and the NHS<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/maxpemberton/ |title=Max Pemberton – Life on the NHS frontline |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> although his earlier columns focused on his life working as a [[junior doctor]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Max Pemberton 12:01&nbsp;am GMT 14 Feb 2008 |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3635625/I-couldnt-have-survived-without-you.html |title=I couldn't have survived without you |publisher=Telegraph |date=14 February 2008 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He also writes a column for ''[[Reader’s Digest]]'' and has contributed to the ''[[Daily Mail]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Dr Max Pemberton |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-1158025/Thousands-pay-100-year-health-screening-Are-falling-scan-far.html |title=Thousands of us pay more than £100 each year for health screening. Are we falling for a scan too far? &#124; Mail Online |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |date=28 February 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dr Max Pemberton |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-1133026/Love-tonsils--theyre-defence-illness.html |title=Love your tonsils – they're our first defence against illness &#124; Mail Online |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/04/05/meow-meow-is-legal-so-i-tried-it-but-will-banning-every-new-drug-really-fix-our-drug-problem-115875-22162903/ |title=Dr Max Pemberton: Meow meow is legal so I tried it. But will banning every new drug really fix our drug problem? |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and the ''[[Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23733642-we-still-fail-those-who-cant-help-themselves.do |title=We still fail those who can’t help themselves &#124; News |work=Evening Standard |location=London |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23707971-blunders-wont-stop-the-great-march-of-ivf.do |title=Blunders won't stop the great march of IVF &#124; News |work=Evening Standard |location=London |date=16 June 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref>

His first book, ''Trust Me I’m A (Junior) Doctor'', published by [[Hodder and Stoughton]], recounted his first year working as a doctor in the NHS and was based on his first year of columns for ''The Daily Telegraph''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hodder.co.uk/authors/author.aspx?AuthorID=32946 |title=> Our Authors > Max Pemberton |publisher=hodder.co.uk |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Grew |first=Tony |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-8358.html/ |title=INTERVIEW: Trust him, he’s a junior doctor – from Pink News – all the latest gay news from the gay community |publisher=Pink News |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Katie Toms |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2008/feb/17/booksonhealth.biography |title=Review: Trust Me, I'm a (Junior) Doctor by Max Pemberton &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> It was serialised as [[book of the week]] on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web|author=15:00 – 15:30 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b008zlj5 |title=Radio 4 Programmes – Book of the Week: Trust me, I'm a (Junior) Doctor |publisher=BBC |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> His second book ''Where Does It Hurt?'' details his time working in an outreach project for the homeless and people addicted to drugs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaydarradio.com/UserPortal/Article/Detail.aspx?ID=25226&sid=89 |title=GaydarNation |publisher=Gaydarradio.com |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/6041942/Dr-Max-Pemberton-How-many-drug-addict-grannies-do-you-know.html |title=Dr Max Pemberton: 'How many drug-addict grannies do you know?' |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qs3x9 |title=Radio 4 Programmes – Loose Ends, 20 February 2010 |publisher=BBC |date=20 February 2010 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He is currently writing a third book to be published by Hodder and Stoughton.<ref name="hhbagency1">{{cite web|url=http://www.hhbagency.com/authors/pemberton.html |title=Max Pemberton |publisher=hhb agency |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> After the publication of his first book, the title of his column in ''The Daily Telegraph'' changed from ''Trust Me I'm A (Junior) Doctor'' to ''Finger On The Pulse''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Health Advice |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/3353670/Max-Pemberton-Finger-on-the-Pulse.html |title=Max Pemberton: Finger on the Pulse |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref>

He is a staunch advocate for the NHS.<ref>{{cite web|author=Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/2208144/The-NHS-is-sick-but-is-it-terminal.html |title=The NHS is sick, but is it terminal? |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He is critical of the government’s introduction of [[Private finance initiative|PFI]] in the NHS<ref>{{cite web|author=Health Advice |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/3356306/Finger-on-the-pulse.html |title=Finger on the pulse |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and opposes the introduction of the NHS patient record database.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/remedyuk/docs/www.rukmag.org |title=R-UK Magazine Issue 2 |publisher=Issuu.com |date=28 August 2008 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Max Pemberton |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/maxpemberton/6787809/The-chaos-of-the-NHSs-electronic-records.html |title=The chaos of the NHS's electronic records |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He has also spoken out against the way the [[European Working Time Directive]] has been implemented by [[NHS trusts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8177878.stm |title=Health &#124; Cap on junior doctor hours starts |publisher=BBC News |date=1 August 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Amanda Craig |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1203757/NHS-urging-junior-doctors-lie-hours-comply-EU-laws.html |title=NHS 'urging junior doctors to lie about hours to comply with EU laws' &#124; Mail Online |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8179000/8179464.stm |title=BBC – Today – Today: Saturday 1 August 2009 |publisher=BBC News |date=1 August 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and about [[Medical Training Application Service|MTAS]] and [[Modernising Medical Careers|MMC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Max |first=Dr |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1544310/In-my-hospital-the-staff-are-crying.html |title=In my hospital, the staff are crying |publisher=Telegraph |date=2 March 2007 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=12:01&nbsp;am GMT 12 Mar 2007 |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1545221/I-wouldnt-trust-this-system-to-select-someone-to-water-my-plants.html |title=I wouldn't trust this system to select someone to water my plants |publisher=Telegraph |date=12 March 2007 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He often writes about the rights of [[older people]]<ref>http://www.maxpemberton.com/component/search/older%2Bpeople/%252F?ordering=newest&searchphrase=exact&limit=20</ref> and those with [[mental illness]].<ref>http://www.maxpemberton.com/component/search/mental%2Billness/%252F?ordering=newest&searchphrase=exact&limit=20</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3355281/Finger-on-the-Pulse.html |title=Finger on the Pulse |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He is openly gay<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainbownetwork.com/download/file/DrMaxPembertonFeb2010N&D.mp3 |title=GaydarRadio |publisher=Rainbownetwork.com |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and has written against the ban on gay people [[donating blood]] in the UK<ref>{{cite web|author=Men's Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/men_shealth/3354388/Finger-on-the-Pulse.html |title=Finger on the Pulse |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and in support of [[gay adoption]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3347256/Trust-me-Im-a-junior-doctor.html |title=Trust me, I'm a junior doctor |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> and the impact of [[homophobic bullying]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Health Advice |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/3356535/Finger-on-the-pulse.html |title=Finger on the pulse |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> As well as a degree in medicine, he also holds a first class honours degree in [[Anthropology]]. His column in the ''Daily Telegraph'' won the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]' Public Education award.<ref>{{cite web|author=Health |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3340812/Trust-me-Im-a-junior-doctor-wish-you-were-here.html |title=Trust me, I'm a junior doctor: 'wish you were here!' |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref> He won the Mind Journalist of the Year Award 2010<ref>[http://www.mind.org.uk/mindawards/awards ]{{dead link|date=January 2012}}</ref> and the Royal College of Psychiatrists' Public Educator of the Year 2010 award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcpsych.ac.uk/events/rcpsychawards2012/rcpsychawardswinners2010.aspx |title=RCPsych Awards Winners 2010 |publisher=Rcpsych.ac.uk |accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>

